06977nam a22010815i 9781501507830DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015078307 a10.1515/97815015078302doi  a(DE-B1597)490036  a(OCoLC)1120720868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aGN34.3.F53 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a301.072/322300aRapport and the Discursive Co-Construction of Social Relations in Fieldwork Encounters /ced. by Zane Goebel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (IX, 194 p.) :b3000 Gleichungen  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage and Social Life [LSL] ,x2364-4303 ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgment -- tContents -- tList of Contributing Authors -- t1. Rapport and the Discursive Co-Construction of Social Relations in Fieldwork Settings -- t2. Looking for Rapport in the Metacommunicative Features of an Ethnographic Interview -- t3. ‘Today’s Episode Is Sponsored by Nü Green Tea’: Rapport and Virtuoso Humour in Group Interviews -- t4. Understanding Rapport Through Scalar Reflexivity -- t5. Doing Ethnography Across Institutions: Rapport and Discursive Ruptures in Jakarta -- t6. Commentary: Rapport in Qualitative Investigation, from Researcher’s Objectivity to Researcher’s Reflexivity -- t7. Sociolinguistic Scale and Ethnographic Rapport -- t8. The Ethnolinguistic Listener: Narrativity and Ideologies of Local Language in Urban Banyuwangi -- t9. The Discursive Co-Construction of Social Relations in Sundanese-Speaking Areas in West Java -- t10. Rapport, Affinity, and Kin Terms -- t11. Recognitional Reference and Rapport Building in the Author Interview -- t12. Making Connections -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn accounts of ethnographic fieldwork and textbooks on ethnography, we often find the notion of rapport used to describe social relationships in the field. Frequently, rapport between researcher and researched is invoked as a prerequisite to be achieved before fieldwork can start, or used as evidence to judge the value and robustness of an ethnography. With few exceptions, and despite regular pleas to do so, ethnographers continue to avoid presenting any discursive evidence of what rapport might look like from an interactional perspective. In a sense, the uncritical acceptance of rapport as a fieldwork goal and measure has helped hide the discursive work that goes on in the field. In turn, this has privileged ideas about identity as portable rather than “portable and emergent”, and reports of social life as more important than how such reports emerge. Written for all those who engage or plan to engage in ethnographic fieldwork, this collection examines how social relationships dialogically emerge in fieldwork settings.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAnthropologyxFieldwork. 0aEthnologyxFieldwork. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aConversation. 4aEthnologie. 4aIdentität. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aConversation.  aEthnography.  aIdentity.  aRelationships.1 aArps, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Debbie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Fina, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErrington, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoebel, Zane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoebel, Zane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHakim, Rafadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarr, Adam, econtributor.4ctb